Yes—that means the dependency coordinate is valid. The problem is dependency traffic, not sts.

An AWS BOM only controls versions; it does not contain the STS library. Gradle must still download the STS POM/JAR and its transitive dependencies separately. 

Recommended GitHub Actions configuration

- uses: actions/checkout@v6

- uses: actions/setup-java@v5
  with:
    distribution: temurin
    java-version: '17'
    # Do not also configure cache: gradle here

- name: Set up Gradle cache
  uses: gradle/actions/setup-gradle@v6
  with:
    cache-provider: basic

- name: Build
  run: ./gradlew build --no-daemon

setup-gradle restores downloaded dependencies from GitHub’s cache, so later builds should not repeatedly request STS from Maven Central. Do not combine its caching with actions/setup-java’s Gradle cache or a separate actions/cache configuration. 

Also remove any of these:

./gradlew build --refresh-dependencies
rm -rf ~/.gradle/caches
./gradlew dependencies

--refresh-dependencies and deleting the cache force additional repository requests.

Check dependency-submission workflows

Look for this action:

uses: gradle/actions/dependency-submission@...

By default, it runs a special task that resolves all project dependencies, potentially causing another complete set of Maven Central requests. 

Run dependency submission only on main or on a schedule—not in every PR or matrix job:

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

Alternatively, capture the dependency graph during the normal build rather than resolving everything in a separate job:

- uses: gradle/actions/setup-gradle@v6
  with:
    cache-provider: basic
    dependency-graph: generate-and-submit

- run: ./gradlew build

This reports dependencies resolved by the actual build. 

Reduce parallel cold builds

Multiple matrix jobs can hit Maven Central simultaneously before any job has saved its cache:

strategy:
  max-parallel: 1
  matrix:
    java: ['17', '21']

Serializing is a useful immediate mitigation, though it is not as robust as a repository proxy.

Best long-term solution: repository proxy

For reliable CI, place Nexus, Artifactory, AWS CodeArtifact, or another caching repository manager between Gradle and Maven Central. Configure that proxy as the only repository:

// settings.gradle
dependencyResolutionManagement {
    repositories {
        maven {
            url = uri(System.getenv("MAVEN_PROXY_URL"))

            credentials {
                username = System.getenv("MAVEN_PROXY_USERNAME")
                password = System.getenv("MAVEN_PROXY_PASSWORD")
            }
        }
    }
}

Do not add mavenCentral() after the proxy when the proxy already mirrors Central; otherwise Gradle may fall through and contact Central directly.

Sonatype’s official guidance for HTTP 429 is to reduce repeated downloads through caching and repository managers, consolidate requests, and avoid aggressive retries. The limit can be based on aggregate traffic from a shared network or CI-provider egress—not necessarily only your repository. 

Dependency declaration

When STS is your only AWS SDK module, this minimizes one BOM request:

dependencies {
    implementation 'software.amazon.awssdk:sts:2.23.12'
}

When using several AWS SDK modules, keep the BOM for version consistency:

dependencies {
    implementation platform('software.amazon.awssdk:bom:2.23.12')
    implementation 'software.amazon.awssdk:sts'
}

Neither form can prevent Gradle from downloading STS separately; caching or proxying is the actual fix.